<TITLE> Kalyanpur shop owners block road protesting eviction </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 3 (bdnews24.com)  Shop owners of Kalyanpur BRTC market Sunday blocked Mirpur Road for two hours protesting the state-run transport agency's notice on them to vacate the market. Police charged batons to disperse the protesters, Mirpur police chief Mohiuddin Mahmud said. Protesters said up to 25 people were hurt as police attacked what they said was a peaceful protest. Five were arrested, they said. Mahmud said they had arrested Azizur Rahman, Arifur Rahman and Mohammad Liton people from the scene and filed a case. Mirpur police sub-inspector Ezazul Islam told bdnews24.com that shop owners took to the street in the morning and blocked the road halting traffic for two hours. Kalyanpur Byabshayi Bahumukhi Somobay Samity Limited in a press release, signed by Nasir Uddin, said BRTC wanted to evict them defying the court order. He threatened tough movement if the arrestees were not freed immediately. A senior official of Bangladesh Road Transport Corporation preferring anonymity told bdnews24.ocm that city developer Rajdhani Unnayan Kartripakkha and BRTC were in a legal wrangle over the plan for the shops. BRTC lost the case and planned eviction in line with the court order and asked the shop owners to vacate the market. He said 87 shops were allocated for 20 years37 were allocated in 1996 and 50 in 2001 alongside the bus depot. The businessmen became angry as they were asked to vacate the market before the expiry of the contracts. He said initiatives were taken to make a new plan and the shop owners would get priority during allocation of shops. The BRTC official said 25 owners had filed a writ petition in the High Court seeking a ban on eviction and the court had given a judgement in their favour. He said the rest of the shop owners were preparing to file writ petition. bdnew
